Practical I: Extracting, Visualizing, and Analyzing Single Networks

Carel F.W. Peeters

Preliminaries

This document contains a tutorial for Part I of the course on Network Modeling for High-Dimensional Data as given during the 31st International Biometric Conference. It assumes knowledge of R and basic linear algebra. The learning goals for Part I are:

  1. To familiarize yourself with basic concepts in network modeling of high-dimensional data;
  2. To practice with network modeling of a single high-dimensional data set.

The slides, exercises, and this document form an integrated whole. The slides alternate between the presentation of methodology and corresponding exercises. This document, then, contains possible solutions to the exercises as well as additional explanations.

We will start with an exploration of the data. We will then proceed with the exercises. These exercises revolve around the extraction, visualization, and analysis of single networks.

Packages

Set the working directory to convenience and activate the required package:

## Set working directory to convenience
setwd(" ")

## Packages (install and invoke)
pkgs <- rownames(installed.packages())
if(!"rags2ridges" %in% pkgs) install.packages("rags2ridges")

The code recognizes if certain packages are missing from your package library and, if so, will install them automatically. Now, we need to load the package:

library(rags2ridges)

Throughout, we will thus be using amenities provided by the rags2ridges package. This package provides a one-stop-shop for the extraction, visualization, and analysis of networks from high-dimensional data (Peeters et al.2022). The exercises and code in this document are cumulative: each exercise and code block builds upon the preceding exercises and code. Code is contained in blocks and in-text references to functions, function arguments, and objects will be denoted as foo.

Exercise 1: Get acquainted with the data

Throughout, we will be using metabolomics data on patients with Alzheimers Disease (AD). AD is a chronic neurodegenerative disease and the main cause of dementia. Metabolomics refers to the collective quantification of metabolites: small-molecules that result from metabolic processes. Such metabolic processes are heavily influenced by lifestyle factors. Metabolomics on pheripheral fluids (such as blood) is of interest in terms of non-invasive measurement of disease-specific biochemical changes.

Figure 1 gives a high-level overview of the data collection process. For each patient blood samples were extracted. The metabolite compounds in the individual samples are then separated by chromatography. The chromatographic system is coupled to a mass spectrometer. With mass spectrometry (MS) small molecules can be measured. The sample is then ionized by bombarding it with with electrons. The individual ions (representing metabolites) are then represented by mass-to-charge ratios. These may be recorded over time. The time-sensitivity in conjunction with the mass-to-charge ratio can be used to identify the metabolite compounds. After processing what we receive as data-scientists is 2-dimensional data: a metabolite abundance profile for each patient.

Figure 1: The metabolite data collection process. Illustration adapted from planetorbimap.com and metabolomicsplatform.com.


The data (de Leeuw & Peeters et al., 2017) are internally packaged in the ADdata object. ADdata contains 3 further objects related to blood-based metabolomics data on various AD subtypes. The data can be invoked by the following calls:

## Invoke data, get to know objects
data(ADdata)
objects()
character(0)

ADmetabolites is a matrix containing metabolic expressions with metabolites in rows and samples in columns. sampleInfo is a data.frame containing clinical information on the samples. This information pertains to diagnosis: AD Class 1 (AD patients without a known genetic predisposition for AD) or AD Class 2 (AD patients with a known genetic predisposition for AD). variableInfo is a data.frame containing information on the metabolic features. This information pertains to the compound family a metabolite belongs to. Let us evaluate these objects:

Extraction

Network evaluation basically has 3 steps: (i) extract, (ii) visualize, (iii) analyze. Extraction is about inferring the network (from the data). Visualization pertains to the effective graphical communication of the network. Analysis pertains to descriptions and inference on properties of the retained network. We will start with the extraction of a network.

Exercise 2: Find an optimal precision matrix for the Class 2 AD data

Network evaluation through graphical modeling revolves around finding the precision matrix and its support. Hence, we first need an estimate of the precision matrix. In this section we will be interested in data for AD Class 2 (i.e, AD patients with a known genetic predisposition for AD). The precision matrix estimate will have to be a regularized estimate as the number of features (p=230) is larger than the number of observations (n=87 for AD Class 2). We will use a proper ridge estimate of the precision matrix (van Wieringen & Peeters, 2016). This estimate depends on a target matrix and a strictly positive penalty parameter. The target matrix encodes prior information while the penalty parameter determines the rate of shrinkage (of the data towards the target).

Hence, we first retain the data for AD class 2. We scale the data, as the features have different scales and as the variability of the features may differ substantially:

## Extract data for AD Class 2
ADclass2 <- ADmetabolites[,sampleInfo$ApoEClass == "Class 2"]

## Check dimensions
dim(ADclass2)
[1] 230  87
## Transpose and scale data
ADclass2 <- scale(t(ADclass2))
  1. Why would you transpose the data before scaling?
  2. Why would you scale the data?


  1. In the original data object the variables are in the rows and samples in the columns. Most procedures in R that operate on the variables assume the variables to be represented by columns. Hence, we need to transpose the data.

  2. As you have seen from the inspection of the data in Exercise 1: the variables have differing scales. As the number of variables is larger than the number of observations we need some form of (Bayesian) regularization to obtain our desired precision matrix. If we would perform regularization on the unscaled features the regularization would be driven by differences in scale rather than differences in signal.


These scaled data are used in the optPenalty.kCVauto function. This function determines the optimal value of the penalty parameter by application of the Brent algorithm (1971) to the K-fold cross-validated negative log-likelihood score (using a regularized ridge estimator for the precision matrix). The search for the optimal value is automatic in the sense that in order to invoke the root-finding abilities of the Brent method, only a minimum value (lambdaMin) and a maximum value (lambdaMax) for the penalty parameter need to be specified (from which a starting penalty value is automatically generated). As we have little a priori knowledge, we will keep the target simple: An identity matrix (the default.target function can be used for specifying convenience targets). The penalty value at which the K-fold cross-validated negative log-likelihood score is minimized is deemed optimal. The output is an object of class list, with $optLambda containing the optimal penalty value and $optPrec containing the precision matrix under the optimal value of the penalty parameter.

## Use kCVauto to find optimal regularized precision matrix
set.seed(1234)
OPT <- optPenalty.kCVauto(
  ADclass2, 
  fold      = 10,
  lambdaMin = 1e-07, 
  lambdaMax = 20,
  target    = default.target(covML(ADclass2), type = "DUPV"))

## Have a look at optimal penalty value
OPT$optLambda
[1] 0.1561957
  1. The ridge estimator of the precision matrix can be viewed as an empirical Bayes estimator. How many parameters does the inverse precision matrix have? And how does this relate to our choice to use Empirical instead of, say, full Bayes?
  2. What is the optimal value for the penalty parameter?


  1. The inverse precision matrix has p(p+1)/2 parameters (as the matrix is symmetric we only need to count the non-redundant elements: those on and above (or below) the diagonal). As we have p=230 metabolites this amounts to (230231)/2=26565 parameters. Even though modern Markov chain Monte Carlo sampling (such as Hamiltonian Monte Carlo) is very powerful, it becomes prohibitely slow when sampling for more than 10000 parameters. Hence, in our situation Empirical Bayes seems a solution to combine some benefits of Bayes with the computational speed of more traditional statistics.
  2. The optimal value for the penalty parameter is: .1561957.


A heatmap of the optimal precision matrix is easily obtained through usage of the edgeHeat function.

## Heatmap of precision matrix
edgeHeat(OPT$optPrec, diag = FALSE, textsize = 3)

  1. Does this heatmap already represent a network?


  1. No it does not. The heatmap visualized the regularized estimate of the precision matrix. In order to extract a network we must determine its support. That is: we need to determine which entries are zero and which are nonzero. Such a sparsified matrix has a one-on-one relation with a conditional independence graph.

Exercise 3: Assess the conditioning of the optimal precision matrix

After obtaining an estimate of the precision matrix, we might like to assess its conditioning. The effect of the ridge penalty on the precision estimate can be understood in terms of shrinkage of the eigenvalues of the unpenalized precision estimate. We can thus use the spectral condition number, i.e., the ratio of the maximum to minimum eigenvalue, of the regularized precision matrix to assess its conditioning. A matrix with a high condition number is near-singular and its inversion is numerically unstable. Such a matrix is said to be ill-conditioned. Numerically, ill-conditioning will mean that small changes in the penalty parameter lead to dramatic changes in the condition number. From a numerical point of view one can thus track the domain of the penalty parameter for which the regularized precision matrix is ill-conditioned. When plotting the condition number against the (domain of the) penalty parameter, there is a point of relative stabilization (when working in the p>n situation) that can be characterized by a leveling-off of the acceleration along the curve. One wants the precision matrix estimate to be in the stable domain of well-conditionedness.

The CNplot function outputs a graph of the spectral condition number over the domain of the penalty parameter. When Iaids = TRUE, the basic condition number plot is amended/enhanced with two additional plots (over the same domain of the penalty parameter as the basic plot): (i) The approximate loss in digits of accuracy (for the operation of inversion) and (ii) an approximation to the second-order derivative of the curvature in the basic plot. These interpretational aids can enhance interpretation of the basic condition number plot (Peeters, van de Wiel, & van Wieringen, 2020). When vertical = TRUE a vertical line is added at the constant given in the argument value. This option can be used to assess if the optimal penalty obtained by, e.g., the optPenalty.kCVauto routine has led to a precision estimate that is well-conditioned.

## Assess conditioning of optimal precision using CN plot
CNplot(covML(ADclass2), 
       lambdaMin = 1e-07, 
       lambdaMax = 20, 
       step      = 5000,
       target    = default.target(covML(ADclass2), type = "DUPV"),
       Iaids     = TRUE,
       vertical  = TRUE,
       value     = OPT$optLambda,
       verbose   = FALSE)

  1. The far-left panel gives the basic spectral condition number plot. The red vertical line indicates the value for the penalty that was deemed optimal in Exercise 2. The middle and far-right panels depict the interpretational aids. Can our estimate of the precision matrix be considered well-conditioned?


  1. The optimal penalty value lies in the domain of well-conditionedness: small perturbations in this value do not affect the spectral condition number greatly. Hence, we do not expect a large propagation of error when using our matrix in further analyzes. From the middle plot, for example, we understand that the estimated loss in digits of accuracy in operations based on the optimal precision matrix is 2. When using a 16-bit machine, this is deemed acceptable. In all, our estimate of the precision matrix is considered well-conditioned.

Exercise 4: Extract a network from the optimal precision matrix

If we have a well-conditioned estimate of the precision matrix we want to extract a network. In graphical modeling this implies determining the support of the estimated (regularized) precision matrix. Support determination is best performed on a scaled version of the precision matrix: the partial correlation matrix. The sparsify function determines the support of a partial correlation/precision matrix by thresholding and sparsifies it accordingly. When threshold = "localFDR" a mixture model is fitted to the nonredundant partial correlations, on the basis of which the local FDR is determined: the empirical posterior probability that an edge is null given the observed partial correlation. Elements are retained if their posterior probability of being present (equalling 1 local FDR) FDRcut . As metabolic networks are very dense, we set FDRcut quite high: .999.

## Threshold the optimal precision matrix
## Retain those elements whose posterior probability of being present >= .999
P0 <- sparsify(OPT$optPrec,
               threshold = "localFDR",
               FDRcut    = .999,
               verbose   = FALSE)
- Retained elements:  310 
- Corresponding to 1.18 % of possible edges
  1. How many elements are deemed nonzero (i.e., how many edges do you retain for your network)?


  1. A total of 310 edges are retained.


The sparsify function returns an object of class list. P0$sparsePrecision contains the sparsified precision matrix while P0$sparseParCor contains its scaled version, the sparsified partial correlation matrix. Again, the heatmap of, say, the sparsified partial correlation matrix is easily obtained through usage of the edgeHeat function:

## Heatmap of sparsified partial correlation matrix
edgeHeat(P0$sparseParCor, diag = FALSE, textsize = 3)

  1. Is this heatmap already a visualization of the network?


  1. Yes, as this heatmap visualized the support of the precision matrix, it is already a visualization of the network. However, we would, for clarity and insightfulness, wish a better or more traditional visualization using nodes/vertices and edges.

Visualization

Now that we have extracted a network, we will try to effectively communicate it visually. This is the topic of network visualization.

Exercise 5: Visualize the extracted network

Visualization is very important for a first understanding of the graph. The very same network can be visualized in uncountably many ways, and some ways might opaque rather than enlighten its structure and properties. Visualization should always be geared towards maximizing information and clarity with a minimum of (visual) clutter. The main function for network visualization is the Ugraph function. It visualizes a sparsified precision/partial correlation matrix as an undirected graph. Hence, the undirected graph represents the conditional (in)dependencies exemplified by the sparsified precision/partial correlation matrix. The code below gives a rather default call to Ugraph. It only specifies the type of graph (type), the size of the vertices (Vsize), and the size of the vertex labels (Vcex). When type = "fancy" a graph is given in in which dashed lines indicate negative precision elements/partial correlations while solid lines indicate positive precision elements/partial correlations.

## Simple visualization
## Circular layout, no pruning
coords <-
Ugraph(P0$sparseParCor, 
       type = "fancy", 
       Vsize = 3, 
       Vcex = .1)

  1. Do you find this visualization insightful? Reason why (or why not).


  1. The layout is circular, and has many features. This does not give direct insights into its structure, such as possible core-pheriphery structures. As such, this visualization might be deemed not particularly insightful.


The result is a graph/network under a default layout that gives a circular placement of the vertices. There are quite some features, such that the network structure is not directly clear. One could try to clarify the structure by pruning the graph. That is, by removing unconnected nodes. This is easily achieved by adding the prune = TRUE argument:

## Pruning can give more clear idea of structure
coords <-
Ugraph(P0$sparseParCor, 
       type = "fancy", 
       Vsize = 3, 
       Vcex = .1, 
       prune = TRUE)

  1. Did the pruning bring improvement? Reason why (or why not).


  1. The pruning seems to do little in terms of alleviating clutter. This is due to there being only a few unconnected nodes. Many nodes that are placed next to each other in the circular layout are directly connected. The circular layout obscures this fact.


Indeed, as there are few unconnected nodes, the prune argument does little to alleviate the clutter. In this situation it might be better to use a layout different from the circular placement of vertices. One option is the Fruchterman-Reingold algorithm (Fruchterman & Reingold, 1991) which tries to position the nodes such that all edges are approximately of equal length and tries to minimize the number of crossing edges. This node-placement algorithm also tends to place structurally associated nodes closer together. Such a layout can be obtained by specifying lay = "layout_with_fr":

## Type of layout is important
## Layout with FR algorithm
set.seed(1567)
Coords <- Ugraph(P0$sparseParCor, 
                 type  = "fancy", 
                 lay   = "layout_with_fr", 
                 prune = TRUE, 
                 Vsize = 7, 
                 Vcex  = .3)

  1. What insight might this new visualization give you about the structure of the network?


  1. The visualization seems to suggest there is a densely connected core structure and a more loosely connected peripheral substructure.


Even more information can be conveyed if we would include information on compound families in the node-colorings. That is, we could color each node according to the compound family it belongs to:

## Colorings may add additional information
## Creating vector of colors (simple way) to indicate compound family
PcorP  <- pruneMatrix(P0$sparseParCor)
Colors <- rownames(PcorP)
Colors[grep("Amine", rownames(PcorP))]     <- "lightblue"
Colors[grep("Org.Acid", rownames(PcorP))]  <- "orange"
Colors[grep("Lip", rownames(PcorP))]       <- "yellow"
Colors[grep("Ox.Stress", rownames(PcorP))] <- "purple"

Coords <-
Ugraph(PcorP, 
       type   = "fancy", 
       lay    = NULL, 
       coords = Coords,
       Vcolor = Colors, 
       Vsize  = 7, 
       Vcex   = .3)

  1. What does the coloring reveal about the core and peripheral structures?


  1. The colorings convey that the core-structure consists of amine, oxidative stress and organic acid compounds mostly, while the pheriphery-structure consists of lipid compounds mostly.


A legend is easily added for additional information:

Compounds <- c("Amines","Lipids", "Organic Acids", "Oxidative Stress")
Colors2   <- c("lightblue", "yellow", "orange", "purple")
Coords <-
  Ugraph(PcorP, 
         type   = "fancy", 
         lay    = NULL, 
         coords = Coords,
         Vcolor = Colors, 
         Vsize  = 7, 
         Vcex   = .3)
legend(x=-1.3, y=-.8, Compounds, pch=21,
       col = "#777777", pt.bg = Colors2, 
       pt.cex = 2, cex = .6, bty = "n", ncol = 1)
legend(x=.7, y=-.8, 
       c("positive partial cor.", "negative partial cor."), 
       lwd = 2, lty = c(1,2),
       col = c("black", "black") , pt.cex = 2, 
       cex = .6, bty = "n", ncol = 1)

You could also export the visualization to a PDF in your working directory. This allows for better plot inspections that merely the R Plots window:

## Export to pdf for inspection
pdf(file = "ADnetworkClass2.pdf", width = 11, height = 11)
Ugraph(PcorP, 
       type   = "fancy", 
       lay    = NULL, 
       coords = Coords,
       Vcolor = Colors, 
       Vsize  = 7, 
       Vcex   = .3)
dev.off()

Anaysis

Now that we have extracted and visualized the network, we will try to effectively communicate it visually. This is the topic of network visualization.

Exercise 6: Find the nodes with the top degree and betweenness centralities

Following visualization we might desire analyzing the retained structure. The simplest analyzes describe network properties at the node-level. Dominant in this respect are centrality measures, which aim to identify the most important nodes (hubs) within a network. There are many centrality measures that capture different aspects of `node importance. Two well-known and oft studied centrality measures are degree centrality and betweenness centrality.

Degree centrality simply indicates the number of connections in which a node takes part. It is indicative of the nodes that are central or influential in terms of the number of connections: more connections could imply deeper regulatory influence. Betweenness centrality measures centrality in terms of information flow. Under the assumption that information is passed over short(est) paths a node becomes central when the number of short(est) paths that pass through it is high. See, e.g., Newman (2010) for more information on centrality measures.

The GGMnetworkStats function calculates various network statistics. It outputs an object of class list with slots for node degree ($degree) and node betweenness ($betweenness). This information can be used to evaluate which nodes sort high centrality scores:

## Obtain network statistics
NwkSTATS <- GGMnetworkStats(PcorP)

## Look at degree
head(sort(NwkSTATS$degree, decreasing = TRUE))
    Amine_9    Amine_31    Amine_50  Org.Acid_5 Org.Acid_19 Org.Acid_21 
          7           7           7           7           7           7 
## Look at Betweennes Centrality
head(sort(NwkSTATS$betweenness, decreasing = TRUE))
Ox.Stress_13       Lip_64     Amine_50       Lip_50      Amine_2 Ox.Stress_29 
    4943.551     4212.359     3021.298     2908.500     2789.298     2574.450
  1. Do these node statistics corroborate your earlier conclusions regarding structure?


  1. Yes, most of the most central nodes (whether from a degree of betweenness perspective) are either oxidative stress, organic acid, or amine compounds. The two lipid compounds that have high betweenness centrality can be found (upon close inspection of the network visualization) to be gatekeepers betweeen the core and peripheral structures.

Exercise 7: Find the nodes with the top degree and betweenness centralities

We might also analyze network properties from the perspective of paths. One might then be interested, for example, in the collection of strongest paths between two nodes of interest. Where strong is conceived as the contribution of a particular path to the observed covariance between a node pair of interest (Jones and West, 2005). The GGMpathStats function calculates path statistics for specified node pairs. node1 and node2 are numerics designating the nodes of interest. The function both calculates and visualizes the strongest paths. nrPaths then indicates how many paths should be visualized in the graphical output. Graphical arguments concur with Ugraph arguments. Let us find the 2 strongest paths between Amines 1 and 2:

## Find 2 strongest paths between Amines 1 and 2
## Determine if these are mediating or moderating paths
Paths <- GGMpathStats(P0$sparsePrecision, 
                      node1   = 1, 
                      node2   = 2, 
                      lay     = NULL, 
                      coords  = Coords,
                      nrPaths = 2, 
                      Vsize   = 4, 
                      Vcex    = .2, 
                      prune   = TRUE,
                      scale   = 2,
                      legend  = FALSE)

Sum path contributions       : -0.00029

As in Jones & West (2005), paths whose weights have an opposite sign to the marginal covariance (between endnodes of the path) are referred to as moderating paths while paths whose weights have the same sign as the marginal covariance are referred to as mediating paths. The edges of mediating paths are represented in green while the edges of moderating paths are represented in red.

  1. What do you notice with regards to the 2 strongest paths when compared to the other paths in the output table?


  1. The two strongest paths (in terms of their contribution to the observed covariance) are also the shortest paths between the nodes of interest. This observation can be said to hold for many real-world networks: strong paths are short paths.

Exercise 8: Find and visualize communities

The nodes in a network often cluster in groups: collections of nodes that are more deeply connected to each other than to nodes outside their direct topological environment. These groups are often called communities. There is interest in the detection of these communities as they are thought to represent functional modules. Community detection, loosely speaking, then refers to the search for ``naturally occurring groups in a network" [Newman, 2010, p.371]. The Communities function performs community detection. It uses a betweenness-based method of community detection, commonly known as the Girvan-Newman algorithm (Newman & Girvan, 2004). When graph = TRUE (default) the community structure in the graph is also visualized. Hence, many arguments that are used in the Ugraph function reappear here.

## Find and visualize the communities for the extracted network
## Finding communities on the basis of betweenness-centrality
## Peeking at memberships can be achieved by calling Commy$membership
set.seed(24354)
Commy <- Communities(PcorP, 
                     Vcolor = Colors, 
                     Vsize = 7,  
                     Vcex = .3)

The same network now appears as visualized before. But now the network also expresses the community structure. The colored borders demarcate communities. The nodes are also colored according to community membership.

  1. Can you give an interpretation of the communities?


  1. We see multiple organic acid, amine, oxidative stress, and lipid communities. Functional modules tend to cluster nodes that are from the same compound (sub)family.


The analysis has revealed certain oxidative stress markers to be central players in the network. Indeed, previously oxidized lipoproteins were linked to neuronal cell death in AD. Moreover, oxidation of proteins is considered to be an early event in the pathogenesis of AD. The analysis suggests that these disease hallmarks might be detected from peripheral fluids. At current spinal taps are the standard. These findings might point to the possibility of a future with less invasive measurements of disease-related biochemical changes.

Recap and look ahead

Above, we have only extracted a single network: the network for AD class 2. The data also contains observations for AD patients without the genetic predisposition (AD class 1). It is possible to jointly estimate, visualize, and analyze multiple networks. We will perform such a joint analysis for class 1 and class 2 data in Part II. The technology stems from this article.
